  "prompt": "What is the Romeo and Juliet law?",
  "response": "The \"Romeo and Juliet law\" is a colloquial term used to describe legal provisions that allow for consensual sexual relationships between minors who are close in age, without being subject to harsh statutory rape laws. These laws aim to prevent young couples who engage in consensual sexual activities from being prosecuted and labeled as sex offenders due to small differences in their ages.\n\nThe specifics of Romeo and Juliet laws vary by jurisdiction, but generally they provide exemptions or defenses to statutory rape charges when:\n\n1. Both parties are minors and close in age.\n2. One party is a minor and the other is slightly older, but the age difference does not exceed a certain limit (often two to four years).\n3. The relationship is consensual.\n\nFor example, if a jurisdiction's age of consent is 18, a Romeo and Juliet law might prevent the prosecution of a 17-year-old who has a consensual sexual relationship with a 15-year-old. The intent of these laws is to avoid penalizing teenagers who are close in age and engaged in consensual relationships. It's important to note that these laws and exemptions vary widely, and some places may not have them at all.",
